# 🚀 Welcome to the Influish Ecosystem!
### Tech Team & Product Orientation for PD & BD

This guide is designed for our new team members in **Product Development (PD)** and **Business Development (BD)**. It explains how our platform works under the hood, how the tech team supports your initiatives, and how we collaborate to build and launch features.

---

## 📱 1. Our Ecosystem & Platforms

Influish is a state-of-the-art influencer marketing network. Our product is split into three main applications:

1. **Mobile App (Android & iOS)**
   * **For Whom:** Influencers (to apply to campaigns, track earnings) and Brands (to manage campaigns on the go).
   * **Core Tech Advantage:** Built on a single high-performance codebase, meaning any new feature is launched on both Android and iOS simultaneously.
2. **Admin Panel**
   * **For Whom:** Internal operations and support teams.
   * **Key Features:** Campaign approvals, user KYC verification, payment reconciliations, and platform-wide monitoring.
3. **Website**
   * **For Whom:** Public-facing marketing, brand onboarding, and landing pages.

---

## 💻 2. Tech 101: Frontend vs. Backend (Easy Explanation)

To understand how our technology operates, think of Influish like a **fine-dining restaurant**:

### 🍽️ The Frontend (The Dining Area)
* **What it is:** The part of our system that the user **sees and interacts with**. This includes our mobile app screens, the admin dashboard buttons, text inputs, colors, and layout.
* **The Analogy:** The restaurant's dining room—the beautiful decor, the tables, the chairs, the menu, and the friendly waiters.
* **Our Frontends:** Our Flutter Mobile App, our React Admin Panel, and our marketing Website.

### 🍳 The Backend (The Kitchen)
* **What it is:** The hidden engine running behind the scenes. It handles our database, business logic, payment processing, background automation, and calculations.
* **The Analogy:** The kitchen in the back—the stoves, the pans, the secret recipe, the pantry, and the chefs preparing the food. 
* **Our Backend:** A modular NestJS API server backed by a secure PostgreSQL database.

> **Why they need each other:** The beautiful dining room (Frontend) is useless if the kitchen (Backend) doesn't prepare any food. Likewise, a world-class chef (Backend) is useless if there are no waiters or tables (Frontend) to serve the food to the guests.

---

## 📲 3. Mobile vs. Web: Key Differences

As product and business team members, understanding the operational differences between our Web platforms (Website & Admin Panel) and Mobile App (iOS & Android) helps you manage expectations for updates and launches:

| Feature / Aspect | 💻 Web Platforms (Admin & Website) | 📱 Mobile App (iOS & Android) |
| :--- | :--- | :--- |
| **How Users Access It** | Open a browser (Chrome/Safari) and type a URL link. | Download/install from the Apple App Store or Google Play Store. |
| **Release Speed (Updates)** | **Instant.** The moment our developers push a fix, all users see the new version immediately on refresh. | **Delayed.** New versions must go through Apple and Google verification reviews (can take 2 hours to 2 days) before users see them. |
| **User Adoption of Fixes** | Automatic. Every user is always on the latest version. | Gradual. Users have to download the new update; some remain on older versions for weeks. |
| **Device Hardware Access** | Limited access to hardware capabilities. | Deep integration with phone hardware (push notifications, camera, local security/biometrics, offline caching). |

---

## 👥 4. Tech Team Structure

Our engineering and QA team is organized to keep our platforms fast, secure, and reliable:

* **Tech Lead (1 - Full Stack):** Oversees the entire product architecture, defines tech feasibility for product requests, and manages the release schedules.
* **Mobile FE Developers (2):** Dedicated to the Flutter mobile app, ensuring a smooth, highly responsive user interface and real-time chat interactions.
* **Web FE Developers (2):** Build and maintain the internal Admin Panel and our public website.
* **Backend Developers (2):** Keep the central "engine" running, managing database safety, security, and third-party systems like payment gateways.
* **Full Stack Developer (1):** Works fluidly between mobile, web, and server systems to help build cross-platform integrations fast.
* **QA Engineers (3):** Our gatekeepers. They test every single button, page transition, and scenario before any update reaches live users.

---

## 🔄 5. Our Feature Lifecycle (How We Work Together)

We follow a highly collaborative lifecycle to turn product ideas into live features. As **PD** and **BD** members, you play vital roles at the start and end of this loop:

```mermaid
graph TD
    A[1. PD Team - Feature PRD] --> B[2. UI/UX Team - Designs]
    B --> C[3. PD Review & Approval]
    C --> D[4. Tech Lead - Technical Planning & Jira]
    D --> E[5. Tech Team - Dev Phase]
    E --> F[6. QA Team - Testing Loop]
    F -- Bugs Found --> G[Report on Jira & Fix]
    G --> E
    F -- QA Sign-off --> H[7. PD Team - Final Review/UAT on Staging]
    H -- Approved --> I[8. Live Production Release]
    H -- Enhancements Needed --> J[Connect with Tech Lead]
    J --> D
```

### Your Role in the Flow:
* **The Spark (PD & BD):** BD gathers feedback from brands and influencers in the market. PD translates these market requirements into a Product Requirement Document (PRD).
* **The Design Bridge:** UI/UX designs are approved by PD to ensure the user journey is clean.
* **The Tech Translation:** Our Tech Lead breaks your requirements down into technical milestones.
* **The Hand-off & Build:** Developers build it, and QA extensively tests it to prevent crashes.
* **User Acceptance Testing (UAT - PD):** Before we go live, **PD tests the feature on our Staging environment** to confirm it meets the initial product vision.
* **Launch:** Once PD signs off, we release the update to the live App Store, Play Store, and web servers.

